# Document: Thai and Burmese Workers (SOC Worker Analysis)

This document explains the SOC worker-attendance data so the chatbot can read the
seventeen data tables correctly. All figures come from the daily attendance records
of the three departments; this document defines the terms, and the seventeen tables
hold the numbers.

## Thai vs Burmese (nationality)

Every worker is supplied by a staffing **vendor** (also called the "Sub-con"). Each
vendor is classified as **Thai** or **Burmese**:

- **Thai vendors:** PPO, WAS, RG, YSL, BigBoom.
- **Every other vendor counts as Burmese** by default. (If a new vendor is Thai, it
  is added to the Thai list; until then it is treated as Burmese.)

Every number in the tables is split into a **Burmese** row and a **Thai** row вЂ”
there is **no combined "both nationalities" row**. If a department has only Burmese
workers, only Burmese rows appear.

## Departments and teams

- **Departments (SOC):** **SOCN, SOCE, SOCW**. Each is reported separately.
- **Teams (stations), 8 in total:** **IB, CBS, mCBS, MS, OBI, OBC, OBS, OBD**.
- **`All`** in the Team column = the whole department (all teams combined) for that
  nationality. (Exception: the Rotation table has **no `All` row** вЂ” see below.)
- **Three time grains вЂ” `Month`, `Week`, `Day`** вЂ” each grain is a **SEPARATE FILE**
  per aspect (see "How to read the seventeen data tables" below), not a column you
  filter within one shared table. Day-grain files are further split one-per-department.
  - `Month` file: `Period` is a short month label (e.g. `Jun`).
  - `Week` file: `Period` is an ISO week label (e.g. `W23`). A week can straddle
    two months; it is attributed to whichever month contains most of that week's
    activity in the source data.
  - `Day` file: `Period` is a calendar date `YYYY-MM-DD` (e.g. `2026-06-05`).
  - The `Year` column carries the year (month/week labels alone don't).
  - **Consecutive has no `Day` file** (there is no daily consecutive metric вЂ” only
    `Consecutive Month` and `Consecutive Week` exist).
  - **`Day`-file rows only exist where someone was present**: if a (Team,
    Nationality, Day) row is absent from the Day file, the count for that day is
    **zero**.
  - **Normalize month references to the short label**: a full month name
    (`June`), a Thai month word (`аёЎаёґаё–аёёаё™аёІаёўаё™`), or any other variant all mean the
    same `Period` as `Jun`. Match on the normalized month, not the literal string.

## Metric definitions (one line each)

- **New / Old face** вЂ” classifies only workers who stayed at **one** station that
  month. **Old** (experienced) = one station **and в‰Ґ10 working days**; **New**
  (inexperienced) = one station **and <10 days**. Workers who **rotated** between
  stations that month are **excluded** here вЂ” they appear in Rotation.
- **Show Up** вЂ” how many days each worker showed up in that period, grouped into
  buckets. **Monthly buckets are `1_5, 6_10, 11_15, 16_20, 21_30`** days (column
  names use underscores, not hyphens вЂ” a hyphenated range like `1-5` reads as a
  date shorthand to some tools, so the columns are named to avoid that).
  **Weekly buckets are a DIFFERENT, smaller set: `1_2, 3_4, 5_7`** days (a week
  can't hold a 21-30-day count). Each worker falls in exactly one bucket for that
  period; the bucket counts sum to that scope's total workers for the period.
- **3-day Consecutive** вЂ” whether a worker worked at least **3 days in a row** at
  least once in the month. Workers are first split by attendance (**<10** vs **>10**
  days), then by streak history (**used to** have a в‰Ґ3-day run vs **never** did). The
  "Active" count is the month's total workers (the <10 + >10 split).
- **Rotation** вЂ” for a given team: **Rotation** = the worker worked more than once
  that month AND also worked at other teams (moved around); **Non Rotation** = stayed
  put. **"1 day"** (OneDay) = a non-rotated worker who came only a single day that
  month. Because a worker can be counted at several teams, Rotation has **no `All`
  department-total row** (it would double-count movers).

A month-over-month change of **в‰Ґ5 percentage points** is considered **notable**
(up = improving, down = declining).

## How to read the seventeen data tables

Each **(aspect Г— grain)** combination is its own separate spreadsheet file, one flat
`data` table, since a metric that doesn't apply at a given grain (e.g. Show Up's
day-count buckets don't exist for a single day) used to leave BLANK cells in a
shared table, which broke automated ingestion. Splitting by grain means every file
has ONLY the columns that are actually populated вЂ” no file ever has a blank cell.
**Picking the right FILE is now part of answering the question вЂ” there is no single
"Show Up" table to filter by a `Grain` column anymore.**

**Day-grain files are further split BY DEPARTMENT** (`SOCN`/`SOCE`/`SOCW` each get
their own file) for New-Old Face, Show Up, and Rotation вЂ” a Day-grain file has one
row per Department Г— Nationality Г— Team Г— Day across the whole year so far, far more
rows than Month/Week grain, which made the combined file too large for the RAG
platform to ingest in one upload. Month and Week files stay combined across all
three departments in one file (filter by `Department` within them as usual).

17 files total (all share the first six columns: **Department, Nationality, Team,
Year, Grain, Period** вЂ” `Grain` is constant within each file, included for clarity):

| Aspect | Month file | Week file | Day file(s) |
|---|---|---|---|
| New-Old Face | `New-Old Face Month` | `New-Old Face Week` | `New-Old Face Day SOCN` / `SOCE` / `SOCW` |
| Show Up | `Show Up Month` | `Show Up Week` | `Show Up Day SOCN` / `SOCE` / `SOCW` |
| Consecutive | `Consecutive Month` | `Consecutive Week` | *(none вЂ” no daily metric)* |
| Rotation | `Rotation Month` | `Rotation Week` | `Rotation Day SOCN` / `SOCE` / `SOCW` |

- **New-Old Face** (Month/Week/Day вЂ” identical columns in all of them, Day split per department)
  `... | Old | New | Old% | New%`
  - `Month`/`Week` files: Old/New = classified workers for that period; Old%/New% = their shares.
  - `Day SOCN`/`SOCE`/`SOCW` files: Old/New = workers **present that day**, counted by their MONTH
    verdict (rotated workers excluded, so Old + New в‰¤ that day's head count).
- **Show Up Month** вЂ” `... | 1_5 | 6_10 | 11_15 | 16_20 | 21_30 | Total | 1_5% | 6_10% | 11_15% | 16_20% | 21_30%`
  (the five day-count buckets; `Total` = workers that month; each `%` = that bucket's share of Total)
- **Show Up Week** вЂ” `... | 1_2 | 3_4 | 5_7 | Total | 1_2% | 3_4% | 5_7%`
  (a DIFFERENT, smaller bucket set than Month вЂ” do not confuse the two files' columns)
- **Show Up Day SOCN** / **SOCE** / **SOCW** (one file per department) вЂ” `... | Total`
  only. `Total` = the **distinct head count** present that day (no buckets or
  percentages exist at daily grain вЂ” that's why it's a separate file with just this
  one column). Open the file matching the requested department; if unstated, check
  the relevant department(s) rather than guessing one.
  - **Never open a Day file and sum its `Total` values to answer a monthly
    question.** Each Day row's `Total` counts everyone present that specific day;
    the same worker appears in a fresh row every day they show up, so summing
    several days multiplies people by days present, not a real headcount. If the
    user asks for a monthly figure, open `Show Up Month` and read the single
    matching row's `Total` directly вЂ” never derive it from a `Show Up Day` file.
- **Consecutive Month** вЂ” `... | ShowUp<10 | ShowUp>10 | Active | UsedTo3day<10 | UsedTo3day>10 | Never3day<10 | Never3day>10 | UsedTo3day% | Never3day%`
  (Active = ShowUp<10 + ShowUp>10; UsedTo3day% and Never3day% are shares of Active.)
- **Consecutive Week** вЂ” `... | GreaterEq3Consecutive | Less3NonConsecutive | Active | GreaterEq3% | Less3%`
  (a DIFFERENT, simpler shape than Month: just two streak categories for that week,
  not the Month file's ShowUp<10/>10 split. `Active` = GreaterEq3Consecutive + Less3NonConsecutive.)
- **Rotation Month** / **Rotation Week** (identical columns) вЂ” `... | NonRotation | Rotation | Total | OneDay | OneDay%OfNonRot | NonRotation% | Rotation%`
  (**No `All` row in either** вЂ” Rotation is inherently about movement between teams,
  so a department-wide aggregate would double-count a worker who rotated across
  several teams. Total = NonRotation + Rotation; OneDay%OfNonRot = OneDay Г· NonRotation.)
- **Rotation Day SOCN** / **SOCE** / **SOCW** (one file per department) вЂ”
  `... | NonRotation | Rotation | Total | NonRotation% | Rotation%`
  (`OneDay` doesn't exist at daily grain, so this file has fewer columns than
  Month/Week вЂ” NonRotation/Rotation = workers **present that day** by their MONTH
  Reading-B status at that team. No `All` row here either.)

To answer a question: **first pick the correct file** for what's being asked (aspect,
grain, and вЂ” for a Day-grain question вЂ” department), then find the ONE row matching
the asked Department + Nationality + Team + Period + Year, quote its exact figure,
and name that file and scope. If more than one row seems to match within a file,
that means Period differs somewhere вЂ” re-check before using either one, and never
combine rows into a bigger number, and never combine numbers pulled from two
different files.
